Speaker Script — Chapter 3: Key Analytical Tools & Concepts
Audience: FP&A engineering team, Google Duration: ~10 minutes Source: Jack Alexander, Financial Planning & Analysis and Performance Management, Ch. 3


SLIDE 1 — Title  (~15 sec)
Hey everyone. Quick read-out on Chapter 3 of Jack Alexander's FP&A book — Key Analytical Tools and Concepts.

I'll cover the nine tool categories the chapter introduces. For each, two things: what it does, and how our work as engineers connects to it.


SLIDE 2 — Why this chapter  (~40 sec)
Alexander's framing is simple. He says most of these tools are useful, well-known, and underutilized by finance professionals. So this chapter is the toolkit.

The job of the toolkit is three things: understand business performance, identify problems and opportunities, and set a course toward improvement. That last one matters — the book is clear that analysts shouldn't just report variances. They should recommend actions.

Same shape as engineering thinking: diagnose, evaluate, communicate.

Our role specifically: we build the data, the models, and the tools that make this analysis possible. Knowing the tools makes us better partners.


SLIDE 3 — Roadmap  (~25 sec)
Three groups.

Basic statistical tools — sorting, quartiles, Pareto, mean/median/std dev. The foundation.

Projection and decision tools — sensitivity, scenario, expected value, decision trees. For dealing with uncertainty.

Diagnostic and structural tools — performance trees, root cause, activity-based costing, benchmarking, and the business model framework with breakeven. For going deeper.

I'll move through these as nine sections.


SLIDE 4 — Basic statistical tools  (~50 sec)
Section one. The foundation.

Alexander walks through it as a sequence. Step one: sort the population descending by a key element — cost, revenue, value. Step two: look at the top quartile, because the top 25% almost always holds a disproportionate share of total value. Step three: apply Pareto — roughly 20% of items drive 80% of the value. Step four: layer on mean, median, standard deviation to characterize the spread. The book notes the mean gets distorted by outliers — that's when you reach for the median.

The book example is Vance Corp's finished goods — 40 products. After sorting, the top quartile (10 products) holds 88% of total inventory value. The Pareto cut — just 8 products — holds 80%. That's where management focuses.

For us: the analyst can only do this if our data has the right grain. Service-level cost, SKU-level margin, customer-level revenue. Aggregated too coarsely, the 80/20 disappears.


SLIDE 5 — Sensitivity vs. Scenario  (~50 sec)
These two get conflated, but Alexander treats them as distinct.

Sensitivity flexes one assumption. The book uses stock price — vary sales growth across one axis, operating margin across the other, and see how the valuation moves. It tells you which assumption matters most.

Scenario is different. You're not flexing one variable — you're changing the entire chain of events. Recession instead of recovery. A lost contract. A new competitor. Many variables move together. The point isn't just to see the new number; the book emphasizes identifying the management actions that mitigate downside or capture upside.

Used by FP&A in planning cycles, corp dev, strategy.

For us: both analyses require parameterized models. If headcount ramp or unit cost is hardcoded, neither analysis can run.


SLIDE 6 — Probability & Expected Value  (~50 sec)
Section three. Probability and expected value.

This is the actual table from the book. Five scenarios — two upside, the base, two downside. Each gets a probability. Multiply, sum, you get expected value.

Look at the result. Base plan is 120,000. Expected value is 117,700. The point Alexander makes: there's more downside than upside in the distribution. The base forecast is too aggressive. Revise it down to the EV.

This is how you sanity-check a forecast before committing to it.

For us: those probabilities don't come from thin air. They come from history — past launches, past renewals, past migrations. Every clean dataset we maintain becomes a future base rate.


SLIDE 7 — Decision & Event Trees  (~50 sec)
Section four. Decision and event trees.

This is the book's example almost verbatim — replace an existing product, or continue selling it. The "launch" branch has four outcomes: exceeds, meets, below, or fails in development. The "continue" branch has slow or rapid decline.

Three things on every branch: a probability, an estimated value (NPV, EPS, or sales), and the secondary decisions that follow. It's the visual companion to expected value when decisions chain together.

In our world: migration cutovers, build-vs-buy, capacity bets — same shape.


SLIDE 8 — Performance Trees  (~50 sec)
Section five. Performance trees. DuPont is the classic example — but the broader idea is decomposition.

ROE equals profitability times asset turnover times financial leverage.

Profitability is net income over sales — driven by gross margin and opex efficiency. Asset turnover is sales over total assets — how hard the asset base works. Financial leverage is assets over equity — how capital structure amplifies returns.

The book's point: same headline ROE, completely different businesses. The grocery industry runs thin margins but turns assets fast — high turnover wins. Equipment manufacturers need fat margins to compensate for heavy capital. Walmart's profit margin is low, but turnover plus leverage gets ROE above 20%.

So the lever you pull to improve ROE depends entirely on which driver is weak.


SLIDE 9 — Root Cause Analysis  (~50 sec)
Section six. Root cause analysis and the diagnostic disciplines.

Alexander's emphasis here: don't stop at the symptom. The book example is past-due receivables. The aggregate looks like a collections problem. But when you break past-dues by reason — quality issues, billing errors, customer credit — quality is the real driver.

That changes the recommendation entirely. It's not a collections fix. It's a manufacturing fix.

The book pairs RCA with a broader toolkit: Continuous Improvement, Six Sigma, Total Quality Management, Lean Manufacturing, Benchmarking. Alexander notes these skills often live outside FP&A — in quality, ops, or consulting — so finance teams may need to partner.

For us: the better our variance attribution, the better the RCA. If our dashboard just shows the aggregate miss, the analyst is stuck. If it breaks by region, cohort, deal stage — they have something to drill into.


SLIDE 10 — Activity-Based Costing  (~50 sec)
Section seven. Activity-based costing.

The book's argument: allocating overhead by sales dollars distorts true profitability. Allocate by actual activity instead.

The example is order processing and customer service — about 1.95 million dollars to allocate. Under sales-dollar allocation, the parts line gets 60,000 dollars of cost. But parts drives 79% of returns and 13% of invoices.

Under activity-based allocation — by number of invoices and number of returns — parts gets 742,000 dollars. Twelve times more cost. Parts isn't actually profitable. Either pricing has to change, or the process does.

This is the closest tool to what we already do. Allocating shared infrastructure cost back to product teams by actual usage — CPU-seconds, requests, storage GB — that's ABC. The metering data we maintain is the activity dataset.


SLIDE 11 — The Business Model  (~50 sec)
Section eight. The business model — and Alexander's main argument here.

Many managers see the business model as just a P&L. Sales, gross margin, operating expenses, op margin. Each line as a percentage of sales. That's the traditional view.

The book is direct: this is incomplete. It misses growth, capital intensity, and returns.

The comprehensive view keeps everything in the P&L, then adds growth rate, asset utilization (DSO, DSI, asset turnover), leverage, and most importantly — ROE and ROIC. Long-term value comes from growth multiplied by ROIC.

The book also warns against forcing one model across diverse business units. Inside the same company you can have one business with 65% gross margins and another at 15% — and both can post strong ROIC if the capital intensity is right.


SLIDE 12 — Operating leverage & variabilizing  (~50 sec)
Section nine — last one.

If you split costs into fixed and variable, you get operating leverage and you can compute breakeven. Formula: fixed costs divided by contribution margin percentage.

Book example: Roberts Manufacturing. Fixed costs of 60,000. Contribution margin of 75%. Breakeven sales: 80,000. Above that, every dollar of sales adds 75 cents of profit. Below it, 75 cents of loss per dollar.

Then Alexander introduces a tactic — variabilizing. In cyclical industries, convert fixed costs into variable. Outsource manufacturing. Use external distributors. The breakeven drops, downside risk drops. In his example, breakeven moves from 80,000 down to about 73,000.

There's a trade-off he names directly: lower profit at high sales, less control over key processes. Outsourcing means longer cycles and less information flow.


SLIDE 13 — Closing  (~30 sec)
So the takeaway.

These nine tools don't live in our codebase. But four things we do are what make every one of them possible.

Clean, granular data — without the right cuts, Pareto and ABC fall apart. Parameterized models — sensitivity, scenario, EV all need real input variables. Variance attribution — drill-downs are what make root cause analysis possible. Beyond the P&L — capital, growth, and asset metrics in our pipelines, not just income statement lines.

Knowing the tools makes us better partners.

Happy to take questions.


